  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and in the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in a neighborhood where many kids didn't have much access to advanced math or science classes, I remember how the idea that 'girls aren't good at math' could make a young person feel like they were failing before they even tried. My parents both had college degrees, but they never pushed me into STEM fields—they encouraged me to follow my interests, which is why I ended up cleaning offices and schools instead of becoming a scientist. Now, as a part-time cleaner in Los Angeles, I've seen how stereotype threat affects people who are trying to break into STEM fields. When a student from a low-income background or a person of color is told they're 'not cut out for engineering,' it's not just about the words—it's about the self-doubt that can stop them from even trying. I think we absolutely need to address this. The key isn't just to talk about it but to create real opportunities. For example, in my community, there are programs that pair students with mentors who've worked in STEM but aren't from the same background. It's important to show kids that they belong, that their skills matter, and that success isn't about being perfect—it's about showing up and trying. I've seen this work in my own life with my children, who are now in middle school. They've been involved in after-school programs that focus on hands-on science projects, not just textbooks. This approach helps them feel confident and capable. Stereotype threat is real, but it doesn't have to define someone's future. By creating inclusive spaces and supporting people from all backgrounds, we can make STEM fields more welcoming and accessible for everyone.",
